{"title_page": "Balloki Power Plant", "text_new": "{{Infobox power station\n| name = Balloki Power Plant\n| name_official = Balloki Power Plant\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| image_alt = \n| coordinates = {{coord|31.1887|73.8895|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country = [[Pakistan]]\n| location = [[Balloki]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| status = Completed\n| construction_began = November 2015\n| commissioned = 2018 \n| decommissioned = \n| cost = ${{To USD|93000|PAK}} million<ref>{{cite news|title=LNG power plants: CDWP clears two projects at revised cost of Rs191b|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1014163/lng-power-plants-cdwp-clears-two-projects-at-revised-cost-of-rs191b/|accessdate=18 August 2016|agency=The Express Tribune|date=22 December 2015|quote=The plant in Kasur district\u2019s [[Balloki]] village would cost Rs93 billion and the one in Jhang district\u2019s Haveli Bahadur Shah town would need Rs98.3 billion.}}</ref>\n| owner = [[NPPMCL|National Power Parks Management Company Pvt. Ltd]]<br>(EPC: [[Harbin Electric|Harbin Electric International Company Limited]])\n| operator = \n| employees = \n| th_fuel_primary = [[Liquefied natural gas]]\n| th_fuel_secondary = \n| th_fuel_tertiary = \n| ps_units_operational = \n| ps_units_manu_model = \n| ps_cogeneration = \n| ps_combined_cycle = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = 1,223 [[Megawatt|MW]]\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac = \n| ps_annual_generation = \n| website = {{URL|http://nppmcl.com/}}\n| extra = \n}}\n\nThe '''Balloki Power Plant''' is a 1,223 MW natural gas power plant recently completed in mid 2018 near [[Phool Nagar]], in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province of [[Pakistan]]. Groundbreaking was commenced by Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] on November 11, 2015, and construction is scheduled for completion by December 2017.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\">{{cite web|url=https://finances.worldbank.org/Loan-and-Credit-Administration/IBRD-Statement-of-Loans-Latest-Available-Snapshot/sfv5-tf7p?|title=IBRD Statement of Loans - Latest Available Snapshot - World Bank Group Finances|website=finances.worldbank.org}}</ref> The project will utilize regasified liquefied natural gas (RLNG) for fuel, with diesel as an alternate backup. A 40 kilometer long transmission line with a capacity of 500 kilovolts will also be constructed between the new plant and a grid station in southern [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-328208-Ecnec-approves-transmission-line-for-Balloki-power-plant|title=Ecnec approves transmission line for Balloki power plant|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref>\n\nBidding was open to international firms for the 82 billion rupee project.<ref name=\"worldbank.org1\">{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/FR.INR.LEND|title=Lending interest rate (%) - Data|website=data.worldbank.org}}</ref> China's [[Harbin Electric|Harbin Electric Company]] was announced as the lowest evaluated bidder for the project on October 2, 2015, having offered a levellised electricity cost of 7.973 cents per unit, outbidding the Turkish conglomerate [[Enka \u0130n\u015faat ve Sanayi A.\u015e.]] and [[GE]] Consortium which both stood in second with 8.185 cents per unit tariff, followed by China Machinery Eng Co (CMEC) & SEFC at 8.304 cents, and [[Hyundai Engineering]] at 8.332 cents per unit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chinese-led consortium termed lowest bidder for power project|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1210939|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Dawm|date=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Project Financing==\n\nPlans for the project call for private sector investment to construct the plant, with the private company then selling electricity to the government of Pakistan at pre-negotiated rates. It is not financed under CPEC projects. As the project is to be constructed largely by the private sector, financing loans for the project do not fall under the concessionary loan agreement which finances CPEC projects, but it will still qualify for subsidized loans with an interest rate of 5% which are to be dispersed by the [[Exim Bank of China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1218917/pm-performs-groundbreaking-of-1223mw-plant|title=PM performs groundbreaking of 1,223MW plant|first=|last=APP|date=11 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref> For comparison, loans for previous Pakistani infrastructure projects financed by the [[World Bank]] carried an interest rate between 5% and 8.5%,<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/> while interest rates on market loans approach 12%.<ref name=\"worldbank.org1\"/>\n\n== Project Troubles ==\nAlong with its sister Bhikki plant, the site faces issues with power generation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profit.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/04/09/punjabs-3600-mw-rlng-run-power-plants-fail-to-produce-required-electricity/|title=Punjab\u2019s 3600 mw RLNG-run power plants fail to produce required electricity|last=Ahmadani|first=Ahmad|date=|website=Profit Today Pakistan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> The Chief Justice of Pakistan (CJP) was given notice of zero power generation by the plants and issued investigations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/05/08/cjp-takes-notice-of-zero-power-generation-by-punjab-govt-built-power-plants/|title=CJP takes notice of zero power generation by Punjab govt\u2019s power plants {{!}} Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> As of November 2019, the current PM of Pakistan Imran Khan wishes to privatize the Balloki power plant along with a few others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/501181/pm-orders-privatisation-of-state-owned-entities/|title=PM orders privatisation of state-owned entities|date=2019-11-16|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[List of power stations in Pakistan]]\n*[[List of barrages and headworks in Pakistan]]\n*[[Head Balloki]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portal|Pakistan|Energy}}\n\n[[Category:Natural gas-fired power stations in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Energy in Punjab, Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox power station\n| name = Balloki Power Plant\n| name_official = Balloki Power Plant\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| image_alt = \n| coordinates = {{coord|31.1887|73.8895|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country = [[Pakistan]]\n| location = [[Head Balloki]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| status = Completed\n| construction_began = November 2015\n| commissioned = 2018 \n| decommissioned = \n| cost = ${{To USD|93000|PAK}} million<ref>{{cite news|title=LNG power plants: CDWP clears two projects at revised cost of Rs191b|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1014163/lng-power-plants-cdwp-clears-two-projects-at-revised-cost-of-rs191b/|accessdate=18 August 2016|agency=The Express Tribune|date=22 December 2015|quote=The plant in Kasur district\u2019s [[Head Balloki]] village would cost Rs93 billion and the one in Jhang district\u2019s Haveli Bahadur Shah town would need Rs98.3 billion.}}</ref>\n| owner = [[NPPMCL|National Power Parks Management Company Pvt. Ltd]]<br>(EPC: [[Harbin Electric|Harbin Electric International Company Limited]])\n| operator = \n| employees = \n| th_fuel_primary = [[Liquefied natural gas]]\n| th_fuel_secondary = \n| th_fuel_tertiary = \n| ps_units_operational = \n| ps_units_manu_model = \n| ps_cogeneration = \n| ps_combined_cycle = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = 1,223 [[Megawatt|MW]]\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac = \n| ps_annual_generation = \n| website = {{URL|http://nppmcl.com/}}\n| extra = \n}}\n\nThe '''Balloki Power Plant''' is a 1,223 MW natural gas power plant recently completed in mid 2018 near [[Phool Nagar]], in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province of [[Pakistan]]. Groundbreaking was commenced by Prime Minister [[Nawaz Sharif]] on November 11, 2015, and construction is scheduled for completion by December 2017.<ref name=\"worldbank.org\">{{cite web|url=https://finances.worldbank.org/Loan-and-Credit-Administration/IBRD-Statement-of-Loans-Latest-Available-Snapshot/sfv5-tf7p?|title=IBRD Statement of Loans - Latest Available Snapshot - World Bank Group Finances|website=finances.worldbank.org}}</ref> The project will utilize regasified liquefied natural gas (RLNG) for fuel, with diesel as an alternate backup. A 40 kilometer long transmission line with a capacity of 500 kilovolts will also be constructed between the new plant and a grid station in southern [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-328208-Ecnec-approves-transmission-line-for-Balloki-power-plant|title=Ecnec approves transmission line for Balloki power plant|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref>\n\nBidding was open to international firms for the 82 billion rupee project.<ref name=\"worldbank.org1\">{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/FR.INR.LEND|title=Lending interest rate (%) - Data|website=data.worldbank.org}}</ref> China's [[Harbin Electric|Harbin Electric Company]] was announced as the lowest evaluated bidder for the project on October 2, 2015, having offered a levellised electricity cost of 7.973 cents per unit, outbidding the Turkish conglomerate [[Enka \u0130n\u015faat ve Sanayi A.\u015e.]] and [[GE]] Consortium which both stood in second with 8.185 cents per unit tariff, followed by China Machinery Eng Co (CMEC) & SEFC at 8.304 cents, and [[Hyundai Engineering]] at 8.332 cents per unit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chinese-led consortium termed lowest bidder for power project|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1210939|accessdate=5 February 2016|publisher=Dawm|date=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Project Financing==\n\nPlans for the project call for private sector investment to construct the plant, with the private company then selling electricity to the government of Pakistan at pre-negotiated rates. It is not financed under CPEC projects. As the project is to be constructed largely by the private sector, financing loans for the project do not fall under the concessionary loan agreement which finances CPEC projects, but it will still qualify for subsidized loans with an interest rate of 5% which are to be dispersed by the [[Exim Bank of China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1218917/pm-performs-groundbreaking-of-1223mw-plant|title=PM performs groundbreaking of 1,223MW plant|first=|last=APP|date=11 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref> For comparison, loans for previous Pakistani infrastructure projects financed by the [[World Bank]] carried an interest rate between 5% and 8.5%,<ref name=\"worldbank.org\"/> while interest rates on market loans approach 12%.<ref name=\"worldbank.org1\"/>\n\n== Project Troubles ==\nAlong with its sister Bhikki plant, the site faces issues with power generation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profit.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/04/09/punjabs-3600-mw-rlng-run-power-plants-fail-to-produce-required-electricity/|title=Punjab\u2019s 3600 mw RLNG-run power plants fail to produce required electricity|last=Ahmadani|first=Ahmad|date=|website=Profit Today Pakistan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> The Chief Justice of Pakistan (CJP) was given notice of zero power generation by the plants and issued investigations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/05/08/cjp-takes-notice-of-zero-power-generation-by-punjab-govt-built-power-plants/|title=CJP takes notice of zero power generation by Punjab govt\u2019s power plants {{!}} Pakistan Today|website=www.pakistantoday.com.pk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> As of November 2019, the current PM of Pakistan Imran Khan wishes to privatize the Balloki power plant along with a few others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/501181/pm-orders-privatisation-of-state-owned-entities/|title=PM orders privatisation of state-owned entities|date=2019-11-16|website=Daily Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n==See Also==\n*[[List of power stations in Pakistan]]\n*